Confidence Scoring (informational only)
After dedup, each survivor gets a confidence score. Three signals:

prox = 1 − API distance (how close to original phrase)
cent = dot(CUI embedding, topic centroid) (how central to topic)
ret = log(1+n_removed)/log(1+max_removed) (how many duplicates it replaced)

Weights = std(signal)/sum(stds). Most variable signal dominates.
Does NOT affect any pipeline decision. No CUI removed. No match changed. Just ranks the output CSV. Delete the entire ConfidenceScorer class → identical pipeline results.

Why Louvain + Otsu instead of just embedding distance?
Problem 1: No single threshold works.
drug pairs:      albuterol ↔ albuterol sulfate      dist=0.03  (duplicate)
drug pairs:      albuterol ↔ montelukast             dist=0.08  (different drug!)
encounter pairs: follow-up ↔ medical follow-up       dist=0.09  (duplicate)
encounter pairs: follow-up ↔ hospitalization          dist=0.15  (different!)

Threshold 0.10 catches drug duplicate but kills albuterol vs montelukast.
Louvain separates them. Drugs get threshold 0.05. Encounters get 0.12.
Problem 2: Cross-category noise.
Without Louvain: 1,770 distances. Most are cross-category (0.40-0.85).
  Otsu → threshold ≈ 0.30 (useless — above real duplicate boundary)

With Louvain: community 2 (meds only), 45 distances.
  Otsu → threshold ≈ 0.06 (exactly right)
Problem 3: Guard efficiency.
Guards are O(n) per pair (BFS). Without Louvain: 1,770 pairs. With: ~30 candidate pairs. Same result, 50× fewer checks.


PIPELINE 2: TOPIC FORMATION + LABELLING
Goal: Surviving CUIs → organize into clinical topics using UMLS hierarchy → label with SNOMED terms → compute centroids.
Input is CUI codes only. No phrases, no text. The builder doesn't know which phrase produced which CUI.

Stage 6: HierarchicalTopicBuilder
BFS walks UP the UMLS hierarchy from each surviving CUI. Where multiple CUIs converge to a shared ancestor, that ancestor becomes a grouping key.
ParameterValueTypeWhy this valuemax_depth5FIXEDSafety cap. IC gradient does the real stopping. 5 is never the binding constraint._HTB_IC_GRADIENT_RATIO0.3FIXEDAt hop 3+, stop if IC(parent) < 30% of IC(current). Catches the "IC cliff". Hops 1-2 always followed (grace period). Example: Persistent asthma (10.8) → Asthma (7.4): ratio 0.69 > 0.3, follow. Asthma → Disease (1.2): ratio 0.16 < 0.3, STOP. Without this, BFS reaches root-level concepts that group everything into one mega-topic._HTB_IC_FLOOR_PERCENTILE10FIXEDIC floor = p10 (10th percentile) of surviving CUI ICs. Meaning: 90% of CUIs are above this floor. Only the bottom 10% (least specific) are near it. p10 not p50 because we want a floor, not a middle. Prevents root-adjacent concepts from becoming grouping keys.max_coveragemax(2, n/√n)ADAPTIVEFrom IDF literature: √n = "too common". An ancestor covering more than n/√n CUIs is too broad to discriminate. Small store (n=5): max=2 (tight). Large (n=100): max=10 (relaxed). Always ≥2 because convergence = covering at least 2.Convergence rule≥2 CUIs, not in surviving setFIXED≥2 ensures actual grouping. "Not in surviving set" prevents a CUI from being its own topic.Subtopic selectionhighest IC first, greedyFIXEDMost specific convergence points become subtopics. Greedy = each CUI belongs to one subtopic only.
Query: 5 CUIs → 1 topic
IC floor = p10([14.8, 14.8, 14.8, 14.8, 14.8]) ≈ 14.8
max_coverage = max(2, 5/√5) = 2

